The Vatican has purchased a low-temperature refrigerator for storing the vaccine, with inoculations to start in the second half of January. eNCA/Estelle Bronkhorst ROME - The Vatican announced its COVID-19 vaccination campaign will begin "in the next few days" with health workers and the elderly to receive vaccines from the second half of January. No mention was made in the short press release about Pope Francis and when the 84-year-old pontiff will receive a vaccine. READ: Pope adapts Christmas plans as cardinals test positive for virus "It is foreseeable that the vaccines could arrive in the State in the second week of January, in a sufficient quantity to cover the needs of the Holy See and the Vatican City State," it said. The Vatican has purchased a low-temperature refrigerator for storing the vaccine, with inoculations to start in the second half of January, it said. Priority would be given to "health and public safety personnel, the elderly and personnel most frequently in contact with the public."